End: While the schools that I've attended have treated me well, my biggest frustration is with how veterans are treated in relation to benefits.  Veterans who have served during the times of different actions, should not be judged as to whether they deployed on that operation or not.  For example, I was stationed in Panama during just cause.  Because I was still stationed there during Desert Storm, I was not deployed to the Middle East.  Between the VA and the different veteran's organizations, I feel like I'm a second-class veteran just because I hadn't been deployed to the Middle East.  I realize that they have different needs, but veterans that honorably performed their duties in other areas during these times deserve the same consideration as to what their needs are as those who deployed.  If my state hadn't offered tuition remission for ALL veterans, there would have been no way that I could have gone to school, because the VA and other organizations wouldn't even give me the time of day because I only participated in Operation Just Cause.

End: 1.  Most colleges do not appreciate or give credit for non-traditional forms of education including military services, service academies and most importantly operational assignments and responsibilities.2. DoD fails to insist those non-traditional educational experiences by documented, evaluated and awarded proper credentialing to be accepted by colleges and universities.3.  Academia generally believes itself to be superior intellectually, morally and with a broadened diversified range of experience; yet truth be known, they are mostly insulated and pampered in a bubble of myopic self-righteousness placed upon a pedestal of their own making and absent of a broad base of experience. In stark contrast to a foundation of experience, like the base of a pyramid built thru a plethora of operational assignments in the Armed Forces. Academia's experience foundations are rather built like an upside down base of experience built upon the apex of the pyramid and only broadened by an indoctrination and complete cultural immersion and adoption of the insulated utopian view of academia which is completely funded by, insulated and immune by the state and federal government.

End: The UNLV Rebel Vet SVA CHapter and our relationship with SVA over the past 7 years has been a mutually rewarding partnership that has positively impacted the last seven Rebel Vet leadership teams at UNLV - For me....As the Executive Director of the Military & Veteran Services Center, I along with my staff manage the MVSC operations to ensure the timely VA certification of GI Bill¬ benefits for our student veterans. Working with my Director of Certifying, Melissa Barber, and my Director of Outreach, Dwayne Gordon, we encourage our staff to look for areas that need to be streamlined, through the use of technology and otherwise, and we problem-solve to create and implement solutions for greater efficiency. To provide high-quality, compassionate service to transitioning veterans, and to increase retention, we regularly seek ways to discover best practices in serving veterans used by other universities, and also offer our learnings to other institutions. Part of this effort includes implementing new programs and events, as well as becoming a member of and regularly participating in committees and organizations that strive to help veterans. We proactively seek to provide expanding resources for student veterans by communicating and cooperating with the departments at UNLV and also organizations in the greater Las Vegas community. We continually update our marketing strategy to recruit veterans to enroll at UNLV, including advertisements in military magazines and regular trips to education fairs at military bases. I can think of no greater honor than to serve our veterans in these ways.

End: Most post 9/11 GI Bill vets depend on the MHA significantly, as being a student reduces time we can work. With that in mind, it is a difficulty to pay back classes we have to drop instantly. Also, the strict amount of months allotted in the GI Bill causes student-vets to put more on their plate than they can handle...which ultimately causes them to have to drop classes or their GPA will suffer. The äóìdropped class pay backäó and the äóì36 months of benefitsäó could perhaps be better tailored to produce more graduates. Additionally, the book stipend usually does not cover the full cost of books. That being said, Iäó»m thankful for every bit of it. Also, the summer adds an interesting difficulty. You can either take one class a month, and you get less out of the GI Bill, or take the summer off, and lose a big source of income for 3 months, which is just long enough to be very uncomfortable, but not long enough to commit to a good paying job. As a result, you have to boost summer employment with short term jobs which hurts your resumíÂ because you look like you hop from job to job frequently.

End: I have noticed a very large disconnect between the student veteran population, the students, and the professors just on my campus. The student veterans have a very "holier than thou" mentality when it comes to courses and other students. They regularly have the idea that because they're older and served in the United States Military they are guaranteed to pass a course with doing the smallest amount of work possible in order to make it through, and plan to use that as a "leverage" against the professors. They regularly chastise other students because they are younger and have less life experience, instead of attempting to mentor and teach. The student veterans at my campus expect full inclusive treatment from the campus, but rarely put anything towards the betterment of the school. It's a very toxic thought process and I have personally started to shy away from the SVA because of the toxic mentality and behavior.

End: When I was an undergraduate student at Western Washington University (WWU), my experience as a Student Veteran was not welcoming at the time. This was the period when the U.S. was highly engaged in both Operation Iraqi Freedom (OIF) and Operation Enduring Freedom (OEF), especially when George W Bush was still the President. The whole school and town of Bellingham, WA always had a protest against any military actions, and Student Veterans like myself felt excluded due to the rhetoric of the protests. In addition, the school did not provide and show genuine support to Student Veterans' rights; and the school's Veterans Office was not staffed very well. Fast forward to being a Student Veteran at Syracuse University (SU), I have observe a huge difference of experience. This school is very friendly to Student Veterans and provide a lot of support. My current experience at SU is very positive and would advocate any Veteran to be a student at this institution instead of my undergraduate alma mater. I wish all schools throughout the US follow SU's exemplary actions when it comes to supporting Student Veterans.

End: I obtained my Bachelor's of Science, Nursing degree because of the military.  I was able to afford school due to the GI Bill and tuition assistance through the Guard but was still working about 50+ hours a week on average to support my family and attending school part time.  In Jan 2003 I had to withdraw from school for Operation Iraqi Freedom and did not return to school until Jan 2005.  In 2004 I was hired full time as a Fire Engineer for the City and was able to complete school due to coworkers that would trade hours with me and a understanding supervisor who had been in the Reserves.Some instructors were very understanding, some were not.  One of the biggest problems was that it was hard to come back from war and deal with the stupidity of college.  The schools idea of something very important was not aligning with what I as a vet considered very important.  It also didn't help that I had not yet been diagnosed or treated for PTSD.Now I work two days a week (48 hours) as a Fire Engineer and PRN/Part Time as a registered nurse working 12-24 hours a week on average.  I retired from the Guard in 2011 and should have had more rank but could not take the time from work for attending military courses for several weeks in order to support my family since I'm the sole wage earner.

End: I returned to Penn State University in 2016 after retiring from 20yrs of active duty service, and previous service in both the Army Reserve (Aug 92-Jan 96) and PA ARNG (Jan 96-Nov96). I am currently dealing with TBI that I wasn't aware of during my service, burn pit related respiratory issues, and depression related to post service isolation and divorce. Yet I still do what I can to help my fellow Veterans no matter how dysfunctional a family we are. Please support your local VFW Honor Guards by assisting with Funeral Honors. If our generation doesn't step up to see that those who went before us are laid to rest with honors, who will ensure that we do?

Motivation_12_TEXT: To actually have a license to do the same job as I was doing in the military. Actually I do more as a Hospital Corpsman than I can do as a Register Nurse.
Fin aid: Vocational Rehabilitation and Employment (Voc Rehab),Federal Pell grant,Federal student loans
LinkedIn: Yes, but have not recently updated it
End: I find that many schools refute to accept military experience for science majors. Most medical programs that are equivalent to job experience is long and difficult to get into. Example would be Nursing for prior Hospital Corpsman/ Medics have to take a TEAS exam prior to applying to a nursing program. Man Vets like myself have found that we score below average in two categories (reading & language) which prevents us from applying. However we score above the average total score. I know Texas Tech school of nursing has allowed a couple of vets due to this same situation to see how the students will do. The students are in the top of the class and are excelling past other students that scored higher on the TEAS exam. If vets with experience can be exempt from taking this exam a lot more Nursing programs will be flooded with quality students that will excel in the program. Thus elevating the strain that healthcare is facing with the shortage of nurses.

End: I was in the Chapter 31 Vocational Rehabilitation program.  They chose an education plan for me to attend Cuyamaca College to earn an associates of science degree in Environmental Management.  I graduated with a President's and vice President's letter, membership in Phi Theta Kappa honor society and I graduated with honors.  Once I graduated, I found out that I can never work in the Environmental Field, due to the chemical exposure that I experienced at U.S. Naval Air Facility Atsugi, Japan from 1989-1992.  My Vocational Rehabilitation Counselor barred me from future benefits in the Chapter 31 Vocational Rehabilitation Program because he felt that it was inappropriate for me to seek federal employment.  My wife was with me at Atsugi Japan.  She was exposed to the same chemicals that I was.  She is now recovering from a double mastectomy from Breast Cancer.  I am now in a position far worse than before I started the Vocational Rehabilitation Program.

End: Veteran attention is cyclic. When everybody was given tax breaks to hire, Vets were everywhere. Now, there is barely a mention unless it is about PTSD or a death overseas.  Vets have  families, and/or other responsibilities. Schools don't understand that. You can tell them till you are blue in the face, they still want them to participate in everything.  Support starts at a System or school Presidential level. If either or both are non-existent, there seems to be little internal notice of Veterans. Student Vets have issues like everybody else, but then have the added stress of broken VA issues. The education side of the VA was okay. Last year, the VA started going down hill there too. The VA is also making changes that the ELRs don't even know about.  You can still call five different times and get five different answers.  I have personally called the VA, asked to talk to a manager and had the discussion about that.  His answer was basically "that's the way it is. the new guys have to learn."   Veteran suicide has to stop.  Is it the cocktail of drugs on deployments? Is it feeling alone after you get out? Is it realizing that nobody cares until someone needs people for a grant to be funded? What seems to work is staying connected. That means face to face time, not locked in a trance on a video game or alone in the country.  It seems like the SVA is now leading the charge on most Vet related issues and getting things done. That is awesome.

End: I'm forever grateful for the opportunity the VA & Armed Forces, through their educational benefits, have given to myself and my family. Where most American's leave school in thousands of dollars in debt, I will have zero. First completing my AA, then BA, and now finishing up a graduate degree, I have taken full advantage of these programs offered to me for serving our great nation. It saddens me when I see my fellow military members not using these amazing benefits. Thus, if there's one piece of advice I hope all student veterans listen to, it is this: Keep pushing forward--Although it seems like a long road, which it will have taken myself 12 years to complete, you will thank yourself, and be forever grateful when you reach the finish line.

End: When I was mobilized I was told by two schools that I would have to reapply. I had been accepted into a nursing program but was told I could not be readmitted without reapplying. Turns out this is incorrect and a violation of the Code of Federal Regulations Title 34 äÊÍ Subtitle B äÊÍ Chapter VI äÊÍ Part 668 äÊÍ Subpart B äÊÍ _668.18. Other reservists were told the same thing by their schools and we almost lost spots in competitive programs. The directer of the VA for the State Chancellors office of California State Schools called me himself to tell me how the school was violating the CFR. Our deployment also did not fall under a title to rate the GI Bill Chapter 33 when we were first activated. I want to thank the SVA for the forever GI Bill and making my mobilization count for the GI Bill Chapter 33.

End: SVA has been very positive and my experiences at CSU Chico and MIIS have been largely positive though there is often age-based discrimination from other students which appears to be related to the presence of lack of presence of a diverse student population based on age. Although law protects discrimination if a student is over 40 years old, there is no protection for students who are between the ages of 25 and 39. This is more evident on campuses with a very small population of older students (large proportion of traditionally-aged students). This is separate from anxiety some students have when they do not know how to interact with student veterans or other military-affiliated students due to a lack of exposure to student veterans.

End: An overwhelming amount of time and resources are dedicated to separated veterans who are students, and rightly so. However, VSOs and other organizations often seem forget that many Active Duty, Reserve, and National Guard members are also students. Advanced education is often a de facto requirement for career advancement, but itäó»s difficult for those who are still serving to receive comparable access to resources for separated veterans because the outreach isnäó»t as well-developed. Members who pursue degrees while still serving are almost always non-traditional students who take classes on weekends, nights, or online. They do so while balancing the demands of military service (often while deployed) and family life. Recognition, outreach, and resources are necessary to help as many currently serving members get the most out of their education benefits and to set them up for future success.

End: I am so incredibly grateful for all the SVA has done for both my students and myself.  I previously worked in Veteran Services on my campus (UH-Main) but transitioned to a new position.  I think chapters could benefit from virtual chapter mentorship/coaching for struggling chapters.  This can be in the form of virtual videos/workshops on how to identify campus champions, garner community support, etc... Also, SVA chapter advisors need green zone training.  I've found that even the most well-intentioned advisors don't know what they don't know.  While mandating training may not be a function of national SVA, making it available for campuses that can't afford to offer green zone training may help.

End: The VRSC at Texas A&M has been a huge help on campus.  When I went through TAPS I don't feel I really got anything out of it.  Granted this was back in 2001, but I feel there was no transition, I went from living on a ship for four and a half years on an Tuesday to a completely different life the next day.  It was a very hard transition and now its eighteen years later and I feel I am starting to get things together so to speak.  To anyone just getting out ASK for help or direction or whatever your dealing with and don't try to figure it out all on your own there's just too much, and get a mentor to help with navigating the civilian world.  They think and act very different from service persons and it can be hard to deal with them but, the quicker you learn to the more beneficial it is to you in the long run.

End: I found it really difficult to get back into the traditional learning atmosphere as well as managing time and life circumstances while in school. Motivation was hard at first, but I persevered. It is very lonely as well. It's hard to connect with fellow students who are much younger than you and it's hard to find anyone outside of school. I became very depressed and still struggle with it.There are also a lot of opportunities or benefits that I was not aware of or missed entirely.I sincerely appreciate being afforded the opportunity to go to school with no debt. I did graduate and get a job in my degree area, but I was also overlooked by a lot of other hiring companies due to age discrimination or over qualification in leadership. I had to accept one with a salary far below the standard for my field. As a result, I live paycheck to paycheck with a bachelor's degree in a computer science related program.Belonging to SVA and my university's veteran's organization was great and I am still completing a certification program that I was eligible for through SVA.

End: Over the Summer of 2019, I have to take any classes available to maintain a constant income and stay in school, whether or not the available classes help with my degree. My school does not have a VRC. We need a policy to require more Summer class flexibility from both schools and the VA. I had to take an incomplete over the Summer because I've been struggling with anxiety, but until I finish that class - there is no way to have the VA arrange payment for that class, and I can't pay out of my pocket. I applied for Voc Rehab as soon as my rating was finalized, nearly 6 months ago in Hope's of finding a program that can help me earn my PhD despite my traumatic brain injury and other mental health issues. Even then, there is no certainty the VA will have any reasonable process to help me. If I could have dropped the class or taken a lighter load from the beginning while remaining financially stable, I would have done so.I would also like to see work-study positions available within Congressional District Offices to help Veterans with their benefits and give Veterans, like me, who seek careers in public policy, a better chance to receive paid job experience to worry about the bills less when seeking experience. Further, the ration of Veterans serving as Congressional staff-members is dismal, and most elected members are Pre-9/11 servicemembers. We need work-study expanded to (at least) every Congressional District Office to empower Vets to seek careers in American public policy.

End: Service members have the ability to succeed and make strides into becoming successful in any path they choose. During the transition it is imperative they can become part of a community near them which can benefit their needs as an individual. This will allow for each individual to understand their actual needs and how they can make decisions based on the support of appropriate social groups to increase their perspective in what their core values and strengths are as new civilian contributing members to society. As a student veteran I have a drive that makes me continue to grow and learn because thatäó»s what I learned in the United States Marine Corps. The foundation that was created during that time is now what allows me to manage myself and my personal endeavors in a balanced sense. When I pursued being part of the Pat Tillman Veteran Scholar Program, I looked for a way to become more involved in my community, how I can learn from others who are being successful in their fields! It was amazing to find all the great leaders who surrounded me and those who were also pursuing to be part of that success! The Excellence Mindset we have as leaders needs to continue to be refined for ourselves and those who will continue to serve our fantastic country and showing them support and community involvement is the most important because thatäó»s what we are removed from in our transition. When I hear the following analogy, it resonated with me because I was not aware how much of an impact my fellow family in arms made a change for my life. äóìThink of removing children from their families and telling them, they must live with a new family, no matter how many times you tell them, itäó»s confusing because the first family aside from you blood family is always first!äó

End: I have had 5 years of experience as a Student Veteran. I volunteered as the Veterans Club President at CC. I am aware of the struggles of numerous Veterans; not only my own. To include varying levels and stages of pushback from the VA and Education system. I have advocated at the CC and University levels for Student Veterans and their Student Families as well.Knowing of and Experiencing the issues between the VA and the Educations system first hand, I forced myself to find alternative solutions to obtaining higher education. Struggling to manage my finances, the requirements of the VA and the Lack of collaboration, communication and cooperation between the VA and Education systems, leaving me and other Veterans in an endless loop of stress and financial hardships was enough for me to resolve on my own what the systems could not and would not. The VA VocRehab put my GIBILL in Jeopardy and it expired unbeknownst to me until checked on it. The VocRehab system failed me and stressed me even more. They made promises of employment, education and security that in one swift moment they denied me. However, by that time, I had made alternative choices and regained my sanity and drive for education (as best as I could : ) ). At this point I am still struggling but this time its self inflicted and involves only my ability to stay focused. I work two jobs and have survived bankruptcy, my home is under foreclosure but I am remaining positive that I am overcoming all that I went through. Even with all that, my life is much simpler and maintainable now without having to navigate those endless loops and stressors of the VA and Education systems.Thank You for your time and allowing me to speak out.

End: The GI Bill is a great resource for veterans to complete their degree. However, there are some short falls as many veterans are behind in academics when transitioning from service, due to a break in school. So, when they return to a Junior College or 4 year institution they are waiting GI Bill on classes that do not count for credit (i.e. predatory English & math classes). The other issue is when a veteran does attend a JC and goes to transfer some classes do not count at the 4 year institutions, once again putting the veterans short of funds to cover college. The extension of the STEM majors to 5 years should be looked at for all veterans, to cover the predatory classes and allow them to finish their degree with out the burden of stress in their last year of school.

End: Most veterans on campus are blending in and don't want to be treated different. Don't give away their secret if they share that with you. With the current political divide, veterans will experience severe backlash because of their service so sometimes its best to remain quiet and try and understand the other side of the fence. Professors on campus will tend to be openly progressive and god can only help your grade if you agree with them. Advice for new incoming veterans on a college campus: If you have a professor that you disagree with on views, make sure you write papers how they think or your grade will severely suffer, even if you provide a good case and have well written argumentative points.

Motivation_12_TEXT: Was unable to find a civilian occupation in healthcare that matched my military training and experience. I had a majority of training facused towards nursing so I decided to go that direction in hope of becoming a nurse practitioner, since the physician assistant program is now a master degree program.
Fin aid: GI Bill (any version / chapter),Yellow Ribbon Program,Federal Pell grant
LinkedIn: Yes, and it is up-to-date
End: The difficulty in transitioning from military to civilian occupation, especially in relation to the healthcare field is profound. I have conducted studies and written reports on this topic and it is disheartening to say in the least... Senate Bill No. 1348, was supposed to help the veterans with medical training transfer military credits and experience, but all of the programs I have spoken and worked with outright refuse to give accreditation for the ACE recommendation military training due to institutional ignorance (none of the university faculty are veterans, and they typically have no idea what the medic scope of practice is for enlisted service members). If someone would like to know more I am willing to share my research on the topics... it is sad to see that getting out of active service most of us are unable to find a job in healthcare simply because the civilians do not know how to accepts our training and experience. It is also upsetting to see educational institutions more eager to receive funding from the VA than ensuring a future of healthcare professionals that are willing to again serve their country in a different capacity for the betterment of all.

End: I was discharged before I could graduate basic training because of stress fractures in my legs and feet in 2008. I was married to someone in the Army and am now divorced raising our child on my own.  I now live with my grandmother, father, and 8 year old son while I attend college. My grandmother has had Alzheimer's Disease for at least 12 years. I just want to be able to take care of myself and my son without depending on family for the rest of my life.

Consent: Yes, I am over 18, want to participate, and take the survey
Transfer reason: Completed requirements to transfer to a 4-year college or university
Motivation: Was unprepared for employment after transitioning from the military
Fin aid: Vocational Rehabilitation and Employment (Voc Rehab),Yellow Ribbon Program,Federal Pell grant,Out of my own pocket,Personal savings,Federal student loans,Private student loans,Private scholarships,State tuition waiver for active duty service members, reservists/national guard, veterans,Parental contributions,Other familial support
LinkedIn: No, but would like to create a profile
End: I truly believe that the government cares for veterans and student veterans, and there has been countless resources and opportunities provided for me since my separation from service. As a student veteran my first college I attended didnäó»t not have a lot of resources to assist with my unique and difficult transition. I personally had an overwhelming feeling of being alone. I was use to being surrounded by my brother and sisters in the military. Please understand that the military did an amazing job with transition resources and employment workshops however, I did not realize that the transition from active duty military service to a student veteran would be so hard mental. This makes sense because the people that help with out processing from the military have never experienced being separated from the military. This is merely an assumption. Lucky, I had amazing leadership and training, which allowed me to be resilient while adaptIng to my new environment. I then had the opportunity to transfer to Northeastern University and they have a student veterans organization that has been a huge help with my transition and academic achievements thus far. I want to highlight that there are countless veterans and student veterans that are not seeking these resources available for them. I understood that I needed to be proactive however, not all veterans or student veterans know of these resources. The other day I was speaking with a fellow student veteran and he informed me he dropped all of his classes because they were overwhelming. After speaking with him for several hours he said that the course work was overwhelming due to additional life stresses. When I reflect on this situation I am fearful that myself and other student veterans will experience similar doubts and life stresses. In the military we have standards and Northeastern has standards as well. To this day I am 15-30 mins early before class. I have missed a total of 5 classes over the course of 2 years. The feeling of getting a C on an exam can be overwhelming because we tend to see this as a failure just has much as not being at the place of duty (the classroom) on time. This might not seem like an issue but student veterans are not your average 19 year old student who is only worried about what they are going to do over the semester break. Again just an assumption. Student veterans have school, financial, and family stresses and they typically lost contact with friends and family while in the service. The transition back to school can feel like you are alone with a lot of problems with very few people that can relate. So something as simple as passing your exam with a C can be the breaking point for any student veteran. Thus, the reason a special force veteran dropped his course because he got a C on his midterm exam in Calculus 3 and he felt as if this was not meant for him. I told him there isnäó»t a GPA on your diploma, but I understood his pain because similar thoughts cross my mind. If I could sum up my experience so far in one sentence I would say it feels like I am on a rollercoaster with out any safety restraints and itäó»s so much fun. Sorry for the confusion and thank you for your time. This was sent from an iPhone so I apologize for any grammar mistakes or misspelling. -Rants from a Student Veteran

End: There exists an unfortunate rules-based Catch-22 that often negatively impacts student veteran beneficiaries of Chapter 31 VocRehab; if the academic program does not allow for at least 1/2 or 3/4-time per term, no secondary benefit such as living stipend or WorkStudy will be permitted.  For me, this is indeed a pertinent fiduciary issue, my graduate study is winding down, with only two terms remaining.  When one course at a time is offered per term for certain academic programs - and such is often the case - a veteran will not come close to achieving minimum enrollment requirements.  Chapter 31 does not allow for elective credit to be added, thus a beneficiary in circumstances similar to mine, loses out on a number of benefits earned on foreign shores...
